        html: '<p>Final Fantasy VII\'s Western commercial success — built on EGM and other publications\' sustained coverage — was transformative for the JRPG genre\'s status in North America and Europe. Before FF7, Japanese RPGs were a niche enthusiasm, enjoyed by dedicated fans but unknown to the mainstream gaming audience. After FF7 sold hundreds of thousands of copies in its first week in North America, every publisher with a JRPG in development suddenly had a path to the mainstream market.</p><p>The game\'s success also demonstrated that Western players would engage with the genre\'s conventions — random battles, turn-based combat, elaborate equipment systems — if the story and production values were compelling enough. FF7\'s cinematic ambition, its emotional story beats, and its genuinely shocking narrative turns (Aerith\'s death remains among gaming\'s most discussed moments) proved that the audience existed. EGM\'s role in preparing that audience for what they were about to experience cannot be overstated; magazine coverage in the months before the launch familiarized players with the game\'s systems and built the emotional investment that made its story beats land so hard.</p>'
