        title: 'The Multimedia Launch',
        html: '<p>Nintendo\'s Western Pokémon strategy was unprecedented in its multimedia coordination. The game, the anime, the trading card game, and the merchandise all launched in coordinated waves designed to reinforce each other — a child who discovered Pokémon through the cartoon could buy the game; a player who encountered a card on the schoolyard could watch the anime to learn more about the character. Nintendo Power was one node in this media web, providing the gaming-specific depth that television advertising and cartoon episodes could not deliver.</p><p>The success of this coordinated launch has been so thoroughly absorbed into gaming industry practice that it is easy to forget how unusual it was in 1998. Most games launched with print advertising and perhaps a television commercial; Pokémon launched with a fully integrated media franchise. The scale of the resulting phenomenon — Red and Blue selling nearly ten million copies in North America alone in their first year — vindicated the strategy completely and established a template that Nintendo and other publishers would attempt to replicate for years. Nintendo Power\'s role in documenting and building anticipation for the game made it part of gaming history in a way that a simple cover story rarely achieves.</p>'
